@Jodonny  What I do as an exercise to get my head in the game when I know I'm not hearing things right, is to either have a really hot or really cold shower - I can't say for sure why this works for me, but if I was to rationalise it, I'd say it's because it shocks my mind into a heightened state of awareness, probably due to the shock of the extreme temperature change. I stick it out for around 10 minutes, and when I go back I'm almost always hearing things the way I should be.

And if I've the time, for an extra boost of awareness, when I come back from my shower I spend about 10-20 minutes just listening to music of a similar genre to what I'm working on, without changing the volume level between songs or when I go back to my DAW. When I stick to this routine I usually do my best work.

I've also *really* fucked up some mixes due to attempting to get them done when I ain't hearing things right. I also have sinus issues, but maybe my senses aren't warmed up. I dunno. The human body is crazy

@JustinLeu is right on. 

Sometimes getting fresh ears is the ticket. I sent a mix to @BatMeckley today cause I know he doesn’t respect anybody or anything, and he came back all compliments and two very actionable notes. 

Sometimes someone just sitting in the room with you while you work is enough to get you outta your head.

@Gazing Wrmth | Mixes & Masters I’m pretty much exclusively in cans and i second all of what Noah said. Additionally, sonarworks for your headphones is definitely worth it esp. for only 70 USD. It will smear transients a bit, but you can get over that if you reference well. Mix quiet and you won’t be disappointed. 

Forgot to mention, because DT 770s are closed back, making sure you have a good seal and taking breaks are critical. You need a 15 minute break for every hour you put in on cans, bare minimum IMO. Without that, attention loss and fatigue kick in. 

Tools like tonal balance control 2 are important. I recommend setting up a Pro-MB with 3-5 bands across the entire frequency range but make them all neutral with no compression. Sub, low, mid, high mid, top end. You can monitor specific ranges now. And for sub/low end, you can turn the gain up on your headphone mix a bit, isolate the low end, and you can hear it a bit better. Make sure you turn your headphones down a bit before you un-solo the low or the sub, but this has helped me massively
